To solve this, we first express both sides of the equation with the same base.
\begin{align*}27^8&=(3\cdot 9)^8\\&=3^8\cdot 9^8\end{align*}

Now,
\begin{align*}27^8&=9^q\\3^8\cdot 9^8 &=9^q\\9^8 &=9^q\end{align*}

So
$$q=8.~\blacksquare$$</think>
\begin{align*}q&=8\end{align*}

Answer: $q=8$

When the circle rolls around the inside of tringle ABC, point P travels the circumference of each segment that it touches. Point P touches each side of the triangle  once during one full revolution, as shown in the image below, and the sum of the semiperimeter and some side of the triangle forms each segment. So, the total distance that P travels is:
 word\P\text\begin{align*}2s - AB + s - AC + s - BC &= s\\ &=7\\ \end{align*} 
 word\P\text\textit{is the length of the semiperimeter and we subtract the lengths of the three sides of the triangle.} \text{ word\P\text\AMC 12B 2008 Problem 25. An illustration in the previous page shows that in each instance, pointP\text{ is tangent to the circle and does not overlap the triangle. To finish, we simply note thatP\text\ \cdot 2\pi \approx 14.13> 14.\end{array}

problem:
Given that $BDEF$ is a square and $AB = BC = 1$, find the number of square units in the area of the regular octagon.

[asy]
real x = sqrt(2);
pair A,B,C,D,E,F,G,H;
F=(0,0); E=(2,0); D=(2+x,x); C=(2+x,2+x);
B=(2,2+2x); A=(0,2+2x); H=(-x,2+x); G=(-x,x);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw((-x,0)--(2+x,0)--(2+x,2+2x)--(-x,2+2x)--cycle);
label("$B$",(-x,2+2x),NW); label("$D$",(2+x,2+2x),NE); label("$E$",(2+x,0),SE); label("$F$",(-x,0),SW);
label("$A$",(-x,x+2),W); label("$C$",(0,2+2x),N);
[/asy]

