draw((7,4)--(0,0));
draw(rightanglemark(P,A,S,9));
label("$P$",(1,4),N);
label("$Q$",(7,4),N);
label("$R$",(12,0),E);
label("$S$",(0,0),W);
label("$A$",A,S);
[/asy]


Then draw a line through $P$ parallel to $\overline{SR}$ and drop a right triangle with the legs being $\textstyle\frac{1}{2}h$ and $x.$ Then $x$ is the height of $\triangle PQS.$ Since $S\hat{Q}P$ is similar to $S\hat{R}P$ by AA, we get $\frac{x}{\tfrac{1}{2}h}=\frac{x+\tfrac{1}{2}h}{h},$ which means $x=\tfrac{1}{3}h.$ Hence, the areas of $\triangle PQS$ and $PQRS$ is in the ratio $1:3,$ and $\triangle PQS$ has the area of $\boxed{4}.$

